                     R
                  
                  
                     IVDGE
                  
                  The Calender of Scripture.
                  VVhearin the Hebru, Challdian, Arabian, Phenician, Syrian, Per
                     sian, Greek and Latin names, of Nations, Cuntreys, Men, Weemen, Idols, Cities, Hils, Riuers, & of oother places in the holly Byble mentioned, by order of letters ar set, and turned into oour English toong. 1575.
                  
                     Psal. Lxxxviij.
Nunquid narrabit aliquis in sepulchro misericordiam tuam? & veritatem tuam in perditione?
               
            
         
         
            
            
            ¶ The Printer vnto the gentle Reedar.
            
            
               AS Gods maiestie in his creation of mankynde, endued the same amoong many other his gratious bodyly gifts, with no one thing of more hy price & excellency, then with the tool of toong for speech & voys, whearby in sort of words one to be able so deeply to strike the conceiuyng of his mynde into the vnderstandyng and sens of anoother: euen so at fyrst for vse thearof, vouchsafed his goodnes (as Scripture sheawthGenesis. 2. vs) to bryng al the wyghts he had made of the earth, and al the fouls of the ayr, vntoo oour fyrst father, to see and gyue them name: that what euer name he gaue them, wear they thearby called. Adam (sayth the text) by seuerall name called al lyuyng creatures, and euery foule of the ayr, and all beasts of the earth. Each of them (be we sure) by so apt and feet a tearm, touchyng eyther the qualitie, propertie, shape, coolour, condition, voys, or sum other such peculiar propriety of the creature named, as whoo so euer could attayn but to sum part of the knowledge of those causes, myght iustly acknowledge a singuler wisdom in the fyrst Namer, and an incomparable mercy in the gyuer of that wisdoom. Accordyng vnto which rule this fyrst Namer hym selfe, foormed out of ruddy clay, and thearby endued with the purest of complexions (as we tearm them) Rubicund or Sanguine, had hym selfe first to name in the Hebru (the fyrst of langages) Adam. As his make beyng the onelyAdam. Rubeus. wooman at her creation, counted moother and lyfe to all posteritie, and (for her breakyng the commaundment) the causer also of calamitie and wo, Adam named Eua. TheirEua mater omnium viuētium. Gene. 3. c. first sun, for the lands he shoold possess, for the moornyng he shoold cause, and for the enuie he shoold bear to his broother Abel, Adam named Cain. Their second sun, forCain. Possessio, Inuidia. the sorow that his death shoold rayse vp to them, he named Abel. After this sort was the leader of the Israelites out ofAbel. Luctus. Egypt, for that he was saued out of the water, called in the

Egyptian toong Moyses. His broother for his constancieMoyses. Sumptus 
                     •…
                  xaqua. and strength in stablishment of the law amoong them, called a strong Mountayn, in Hebru Aaron. The moother ofAaron. Mon
                     •…
                   
                  
                     •…
                  ortis. oour raunsomer Christ, for the prerogatiue which by that byrth abooue all oother, she shoold be blessed withall, wasMa
                     •…
                  ia. Exaltata. named Exalted, in Hebru Maria. Her sun our Redeemer vouchsafed to haue name in remembrauns of his mercy Iesus, that is, health or Saluation. His foregoer, for that heI E S V S. Salus, 
                     •…
                  aluator. shoold be Christes messenger, and for the speciall grace whear with he shoold excell, was called Ioannes, which is
                  
                     •…
                  oannes, domini g
                     •…
                  atia. an Angel, a messenger, or the grace of God. And after this rate may it wel be vnto vs a matter not onely not incredible, but also vndoutable, that all proper names of all things in al nations, wear vpon like foundation grounded at fyrst. So haue we & heer we of Names amoong vs, sum as I 
                  •…
               inde, out of the Greek, as Agnes, that signifieth a virgin, or chast: Agatha, Good: Andreas, Manly: Alexander, a Succorman: Actaeon, a Coastman: sum out of ye Latin, as Adeodatus, gyuen of God: Albion, oour Cuntrey, so called of the whyte Cleeues: Agrippa, of a hard byrth: sum out of oour auncient brittish, as Apprice, the sun of Rese: Aburgeuenny, (short Aburgenny,) the moouth of the ryuer Geuenny in Wales: Armoric, vpon the sea, the hither coast of Frauns and Flaunders. So haue we out of oour antike Saxony (whearvpon our English grewe) this name Adelmton (which amiss we call Edmonton) that soundeth in oour English now, the noble town, or town of noble men: Adelred, (short Aldred) noble counsel: Alboro, olld Town: Audley, or rather Adeley, The Princes, or the noble Iland. But as all thing ar found toly so in daunger of obliuions dayly ouertreadyng, or at least so to be subiect vnto corruption or chaunge to the woors, (the very footpath to forgetfulness) that hard it is to hold the remembrauns of beginnings (though of matters newe) and more hard a great deel to fetch out the originall of olld, so yet to bring proper Names to the reason and cause of theyr fyrst callyng, and so to keep them in memory, diuers learned men at sundry tymes and places (I vnderstand) haue sundryly well occupyed

them selues. Whearof too in especial for the Names in the holy Byble, one called Frauncis Ximenes, sumtyme an Archbishop of Tolede in Spayn, the oother of oour days now, Iohn Arquery a Bourdeauser. Out of both these (the one made to supply that the oother wāted) hath thear been compounded a perfit Calender according to the title of the book: whearin is syrst set the name, then the toong whearof it is: then the name expounded into Latin by the one or the oother, as best serues: and after put into our English for oour Cuntrey, which was the cheef cause of the trauayl taken: Lastly is thear added to the woord a note, both of the person or thyng what it was, and also of the book and chapter whear the same is mentioned. So the commoditie of this Calender consydering with my self, how pleasaunt for varietee, and profitable for knowledge it mought be vnto all: and thearwith how aptly it mought square with the trauayle I haue in hand in the reprintyng of oour English Byble: I could not stay me, but to vse the diligens and cunning I could, to get the copy soon into my hand. Which as with good curtesy it was deliuered me, so thought I it my part agayn, redyly fyrst in this small volume to impart it vnto you. If ought ye fynde in it more profitable then is in the Title vaunted: deem ye as I doo, to take that in good part, and the residue to the best: for as a ge
                  •…
               le ear hartens a good toong, so dooth a curteous construction make a wyllyng wryter.
            
               Fare ye hartely well in Christ,
               
                  this. ix. of Aprill. 1575. Anno regni Reginae nostrae feliciss. xvij.
                  
               
            
         
         
            
            
               ¶ Authorum, èquorum monumentis, ver
                  borum interpretationes, ac Dictionarium suum Theologicum contexuit Arquerius, operi suo praeposuit Catalogum: Quem quò magis tot celebres viros in hoc thematis genere operam nauare non poenituisse, atque quò sedula istius pij hominis industria planè constet, buic quoque opusculo annectere operaepretium videbatur.

               Cui quidem Arquerij sedulitati, vernaculus hic noster interpres adiecit etiam Roberti Stephani (Francisci Francorum Regis Impressoris) hominis de reliter aria optimè meriti: atque Francisci Ximenis Archiepiscopi Toletani, Praesulis hic summè industrij, ea Nominum interpretamenta quae aliàs desyderabantur. Quorum ille scripsit. 1540. hic autem dum Academiam Complutensem Hispaniarum celeberrimam (iuxta Damian. à Goes) in Regne Castilia instituit.

                  Ecstasis.
                  
                     Graec. Arq. Mentis excessus. Pro rei magnitudine obstupescens animus. Spiritualis contemplatio, quasi anima è corpore excedens: An out passing of the mynd, when the mynd is astonyed for the greatnes of a thing. An inward beeholding. As it wear a soll passing oout of the body.

                     A die Septimo, infantulis vmbilici recrementa decidunt. Post bis septem, oculi ad lumina sequaces. In tertio Septenario, oculos, vultusque validiores huc illuc obuertūt. Post quintum mensium Septenarium, lac nutricis respuit.

                           •…
                        t) nudo capite incedere, ex religione non erat phas, aliàs autem pileum si quando propter aestum ferre non valentes, capit a quòd filo ligarent, Filaminies dicti: Ducum, qui Reges obseruarent: Augurum, qui in futuris solum praedicendis occupati: Vestalium, quibus sacrarum ad Deos precum & perpetui Ignis cura: Fecialium, à feriendo vocati, penes quos Belli Pac
                           •…

                  Septimū 
                     suū
                      Mensem Hebraeis nunc Elul, nunc Thisri appellatū, eò aequius credere est, quod eorum Nisan, & noster aliquando Martius▪ 
                     quandoque Aprilis▪ 
                     (quantum diuersa dierum in Mensibus apud vtros
                           
                              
                           
                           que
                         patitur ratio) maximè conueniūt. In hoc autem Nisan (nostro vt plurimum Martio, Sole opposito in Ariete) quoniam Israelitae ab Aegyptiaca liberati seruitute fuerant, ideo annum Moyses vel potius, Dominus ipse exordiri & quotannis Phase Festum, in bisseptimo Mensis die celebrari sanciuit. Postmodum Romulus eundem Mensem Martium à Marte (cuius filium omninò se credi voluit) denominari, & suum quoque annum (iuxta Bedam)hinc iniri instituit. Quo Mēse, Cyprij in suo Aphrodisaeo et Cappadoces in suo Tirice annum etiam inchoant. Quin etiam ab eo die quo Salus humano generi per Angelum Gabrielem B. Virgini Mariae annuntiata 25. Mensis Martij, nos quoque (sicuti & Pisani) annum faustò incipimus.
                  
                  Martio igitur annnum sic exordiente, September quin in septimum se fundat Mensem, atque quin eo potissimùm in loco (nempè Iudaea) sic computetur, vbi primò Elizabeth excogitatum & haberi ceptum fuerit in appellationis nomen, nemo iusté inficias ire queat. Qui aliquibus September quasi septimus imber dictus, nonnullis autem illud Ber sillabicam tantùm adiectionem esse tradentibus.

                     Isthaec quoque ex memoria adhuc recenti. 
                     fidem parua manu sub ducibus Somerseto et Northumbriae (tunc Comite VVarwicense) supra 15.                      Sic & 20. istius eiusdemque Mensis die, Tanta vis Tempestatis inundauit circa
                     Appendic. Cariconis. 
                     Romam ad 4. horas, vt viderētur omnia ruitura et in diluuium abitura. Vrbs ipsa coelo tacta in Palatio S. Georgij ad aedes Laurentij in lucina, vbi et penè dirutum Cāpoflorae obuersum Palatium. Cardinalis Triuultij Palatium multò grauiorē passum cladem. Specula etiam quaedam ad Pontis Sixti finem citra Tiberim inscripta Aldigeria, sua mole concidens tres homines obruit.
                  
                  
                     In Romanorum fastis, dies iste decimus Romanis notatus ater & infaustus (sicuti
                     Aul. Gell. 
                     et reliquus (vt videtur) Mensis) at Anglis quidem candidus et felix satis. Non recens igitur aut fortuita, vt videtur inter nos & Romanos antipathia: quae, nisi resipiscant perpetua vt sit orandum.
                  
                  Boloniam in littore Armorico, Galliae propugnaculum tum ex aediti natura loci, tum copijs et bellicis machinis eo tempore instructissimum, Magnanimus idē princeps Henricus octauus formidoloso bombardarum ictu, medio primùm die strenuè assilit quatitque: nec sumptibus aut animi corporisúe laboribus vllis vnquam postea parcens, donec obsidione circunducta vndique tam arctè compresserat, vt ad plus minus quater septem dies ad deditionē coegerit: bisseptimo istius Septemb. die. 1544. Vidit istaec, qui scripsit haec, Amanuensis tum (indignus licet) splēdidiss. Dynastae D. Henrico Comiti Arundel, viro tam antiquae Nobilitatis stemmate et virtute bellica, quàm cō
                        silij prōptitudine semper claro: qui fide atque sollicitudine singulari Militae Tribunum (summum Mariscallum vocant) suo principi charissimus id temporis agebat.

Ramus) aut in Astraeam sydus, coneinnè quadret. ita carmen est longè sublimius quàm aut in ipsum Asinium Pollionem, (hominem tantùm Consularem) aut in aeditum suum tum temporis infantem Saloninum aequa ratione competere queat: aut interim praeterquàm in hanc vnam Reginam nostram, in mortalium vllum.
                  
                  
                     Nanque, vbi tandem gētium, aut quaenam vnquam illa noua Progenies alto sic demissa coelo, quàm apud nos haec Princeps nostra? Cui vnquā tam iustè hae voces referri possunt, Virgo: quàm sacrae, piae, innuptae, coelibi? Regna, quàm tot Regnorum Reginae? Saturnia: hoc est aurea pacata, quieta: quàm augustae, felici, pacificae nostrae Reginae ELIZABETH, Dei sui Saturitati, Iuramento, Septimo? Quam autem vt certius ac tanquam digito commonstrasse Poēta videatur, addit:
                  
                  
                     Illa deûm accipiet vitam, diuisque videbit
                     Permistos heroas, & ipsa videbitur illis:
                     Pacatumque reget patrijs virtutibus orbem.
                  
                  
                     Annon ad amussim in Principe nostra haec completa omnia? Quae Deûm induens vitā videt caeteros & quae gloriosè tam conspicua eisdem vicissim visenda redditur. Et quis vel quaenam atauis aedita regibus, patrijs virtutibus tam pacatum vnquam rexit Britannicum Orbem quàm haec sua Celsi udo? Orbem certè: quia nec minus Britannia (Monarchia tam Augusta cum siet) Orbis, quàm Roma: nec magis Roma, quàm Britannia. Praedicit & Vates commoda▪ tam faustum regimen quae sint consequutura, sic.
                  
                  
                     
                     Molli paulatim flauescet campus arista,
                     Et durae quercus sudabunt roscida mella.
                  
                  
                     Faecundam scilicet (inter caetera fausta) annonae copiam & rerum affluentiam: Et certè vberiorem frugum prouentum, quàm sub hac nostra Principe non vidit quisquā. In cuius quidem felicitatis diuturnitatem, multa & saecula praececinit futura vates, hijs verbis:
                  
                  
                     Talia secla suis dixerunt, currite fusis
                     Concordes stabili fatorum numine Parcae.
                  
                  
                     In qualibus saeculis hucusque, vates vt non sit vanus, (& summo suae Deo Laudes) liberè, beatè, & pacatè, viuimus, ver samur, fruimur: ita vt apud nos verè,
                  
                  Concordes Parcae sic sua Fila trahunt.
                  
                     Tandem Maro è longinquo tanquam praesens contuitus, & Personae augurium & deplorandas vicinorum Ditiones Mundumque, intestinis adeò dissidijs, flammis, caedibus, terra marique horridè tumultuantem, flagrantem, & dilaniatum: atque hinc immani malorum pondere non modo nutantem sed & tantum non corruentem, quem sua Maiestas sola sustinere habet: blanda eam primùm pro sua Heroica dignitate Vates
                     Heroina Pa
                           •…
                        
                        fex. 
                     compellans, hijs calamitatibus in subueniendo praesentis temporis honores vt aggrediatur, hortatur: quò fiet (dis
                           •…
                        rtis vaticinij verbis enuntiasse videtur) vt hinc per eam venturo saeculo fausta, pacata, & laeta reddantur omnia, sic.
                  
                  
                     Aggredere ò magnos (adsunt modo tempora) honores,
                     Chara Deûm Soboles magnum Iouis incrementum.
                     Aspice conuexo nutantem pondere Mundum,
                     Terrasque, tractusque maris, coelumque profundum
                     Per te venturo laetentur vt omnia saeclo.
                  
                  
                     Vllo ergo alium verè hoc Oraculo designasse, quàm illustrissimam Reginam nostrā (licet alij aliàs (quàm ritè, viderint illi) detorsisse contenderint) nulli iurè in dubium obueniri debet.
                  
                  
                     Quin potius, quemadmodū nonnulli Arthuri, nec vllus & nomine & reuerà Arthurus praeter quàm vrsinis viribus robustissimus ille nostras Britannus: Multi Titi, naec vllus praeter vnum illum honoribus splendidissimum Vespasiani filium Romanorū Principem integrè Titus: Complures Caroli, neque quisquam praeter potentissimum. Carolum illum agnomine Magnum ritè, Carolus: Crebri Ioannes neque vllus iustè, praeter
                           
                              
                           
                           que

                     Conspicuus, magnus, clarusque ab honoribus omnis:
                     Quilibet ac horum quo dignior atque beatum
                     Se magis esse cupit, magis hinc est officiosus,
                     Principis vt tantae possit subijsse fauorem:
                     Gratia nec meritis tua defuit vlla vicissim,
                  
                  
                     Sunt tibi gemmiferae Dominae, Chorus estque puellae
                     Floridus, Archei non infima gratia celsi:
                     Quarum vt quaeque sua est specie spectabilis ipsa,
                     Copia iudicium sic ista morabitur omne.
                  
                  
                     Huic Roseo niueae decorantur muricae malae,
                     Illa venustantem Candorem habet ora pudicum,
                     Vni Pallor vt est, alij est Fuscedo decori,
                     Perseus Andromedam fuscam sic praetulit olim:
                     Forma decet vultus hanc Sphaerica, Longior illam,
                     Thessalicae qualis laudatur Lâodomeiae:
                     Auricomae Spiris aliae ceu lumina fulgent,
                     Ac graciles tereti nonnullae corpore praestant,
                     Vt decorant alias ornataque Pepla vicissim.
                  
                  
                     Atque vt honorificè tempus fallatur ab illis,
                     Aurea dumque comis nectat Pars retia flauis,
                     Et Pars fila trahat varios pingentia flores,
                     Haec legat historias fidas, lepidumúe libellum,
                     (Hos qui non laedant moresúe, pudicitiamúe)
                     Siue alijs promptè narret quae legerit antè:
                     Altera dum dulci moduletur forsitan ore,
                     Aut si quae (quam iusseris) vna tripudiet vlla,
                     Dulcisonamue chelym placido cum murmure pulse▪
                     
                     Istáue dum ludat, blandum siuè rideat illa:
                  
                  
                     Hic genus ingenuum si quis consyderet harum,
                     Qualis & ornatus, quanta & praestantia formae,
                     Eximios mores, animi si denique dotes:
                     Supra mortales has forsan iudicet, atque
                     Semideas, Musas, aut Nymphas ad minus esse.
                     Id quadam & ratione quidem fit, Namque vbi Nymphae
                     Sint, nisi ad alma suae venerandae Archeia Dianae?
                     
                        Non Ephesi dico vanae Scythicaeue Dianae,
                     Eius at Excelsae quae sit Regina Britannûm:
                     Augusta, & merito vastum cantanda per Orbem,
                     Diuaque perpetuum ex meritis celebranda per Aeuum.

                        Claraque fulgentis virtutis flamma coruscat.
                  
                  
                     Inde sedet Comes & comis Lercestrius, Heros
                     Nobilis ingenuè, generoso pectore spirans,
                     Integer, & morum candore notabilis ipso,
                     Prudens, munificus, philomusus, sympathus, aequus,
                     Et (quod 
                           •…
                        ure quidem summè est laudabile) praeter
                     Corporis ingenui, praeclaraque munera mentis,
                     Is quò plura potest prodest hoc amplius omni.
                     Spectata antiquaque fide qui sit tibi semper:
                     Non auri, (vt par est) census, non denique tantum
                     Vitae quàm vestri studiosus maxima Princeps:
                     Certè mutuus hinc Honor est ipsique locoque.
                  
                  
                     At consultorum iusto numerouè Sophorum
                     Concilij desit neu tantae Principis vllus,
                     Addit honoratum vestra ad Prudentia coetum
                     Primates quinos: Quorum à rationibus vnusPrāclscus Knolles Miles, The. saurarius Aulae.
                     
                     Aulae, & fisci Praefectus, Summa pietate
                     Knollus: prudens, mentis iustae, serius, & quo
                     Arbitrij vestri non obseruantior vllus.

                     Bellica, Ciuica, vis praestans manus ingenijque

                     Et cui solliciti exquisita peritia

                     Astronomus, Physicusque, Theologus, insuper omni
                     Eximiè multifaria tam structus in arte,
                     Vt sedes in eo Musae fixisse putentur.

                        Radulphus Sadleyr Miles, Cancellarius Ducat
                              •…
                           s Laucastr.
                     
                     Ambo graues, meritae fidei Archigrammateique:
                     Ordouicorum ille est, Mediolanique Ducatus,
                     Hic verò vestri Census, Proquaestor et aeris.
                     Ambo conspicui ingenijs felicibus, atque
                     Ornati multum varijs splendoribus ambo.
                     Rebus in externis ad amussim exercitus ille,
                     Hic varias linguas, inopinas callet & artes.
                     Est ad opusque obeunda negotia dexter vterque,
                     Prouidus inprimis, felix, & sedulus, vt qui
                     Principibus fuerint (vestris maioribus) alti.
                     In quorum rebus versati sep è diuque.
                     
                        Hinc sibi congesta est tanta experientia prudens,
                     Commoda quae nunc sit, fuerat velut vtilis olim.
                  
                  
                     Et sicut sacer iste (sua pro parte) Senatus
                     Prospicit, atque cauendo consulit optima quaeque:
                     Sic Regem qui iustius aut clementius vllum,
                     Nobilius, prudentius aut felicius vnquam.
                     Quàm tua Maiestas longo tam tempore rexit,
                     (Non ego vana loquor) vidit Brittannia nunquam.
                  
                  
                     Id cui si dubium, praesentis conferat aeui
                     Secum tempus, & historias, & saecula prisca:
                     Marcidus inuidia vel Zoilus hoc fateatur.
                  
                  
                     Augustum hoc Regimen rarum & tam suspiciendum
                     Efficit imprimis, ô Illustrissima Princeps:
                     Vt verus pura Cultus cum relligione,
                     Firmus Maiestati amor & reuerentia vestrae,
                     Sacra magistratus vigeat legumque Potestas.
                     Iustitia, ac optata domi Pax, Copia rerum,
                     Atque foris stabili vicinia foedere nexa.
                  
                  
                     Ac vt nunquam offensa probo sis iusta cuiquam.
                     Sed quo quis probior sit, ei tu charior hoc sis:
                     Atque vt mirificè te plurima suspiciat Gens,
                     Inuideatque maligna, audet contemnere nulla:
                     Sic Germanus amat, colit et te Gallia blanda,
                     Intonat igniuomo furialis fulmine papa,
                     Necquicquam furit intus, deuouet, aestuat, odit,
                     Inuidet, inuidiaque sua maciandus ab ipsa.
                     Italus indignans stupet, Aemulus & reueretur;
                     Hispanus: Moschus, Sueuus, longeque petitam
                     Captatamicitiam: Scoti meritò venerantur
                     Vicini, framea et clypeus quibus vsque fuisti:
                     Poscit opem Teuto lacer atque tyrannide pressus,
                     Et timet ac iniustae offensae poenitet, Alba.
                  
                  
                     Vt fuga vel technae nequeant tutarier hostes,
                     Quin submissa pedum fiant scamnella tuorum.
                  
                  
                     Sic tam saepè rebellis, transfuga, proditor: atque
                     Census in offensam votusque tuique tuorum
                     Impia Papalis quem conspiratio misit:
                     Sic Papistarum peruersa hic turba superstes,
                     In felices quique tuas cecidère manus: vtM
                              •…
                           rum valde quanta primo
                              •…
                            Papistarnm caterua in Reginae Mariae obitu, vsque ad internecionem vná & simul cō
                           
                           
                              •…
                           abuerit.
                     
                     Perfida papicolas, paulò quos nexuit ante
                     Coniuratio, (nubila ceu Sol aureus atra)
                     Introitus felix in Regnum dispulit ipse.
                  
                  
                     Tot moriuntur enim confestim, constet vt illos
                     Interijsse maligno animi moerore rebellis,
                     
                        Aut ex antipathia contra te et pietatem.
                     Augustum (hoc inquam) Regimen tam suspiciendum
                     Efsicit immensum longè lateque per orbem
                     Vt tua spargatur celebris nunc vndique fama,
                     Et thema fiat perpetuis annalibus amplum.
                     Atqui, ô duram infelicis Patteni sortem!
                     Tristis & immitis pròh inclementia Fati!
                     Veh mihi, quem miserum sic in decliuibus annis
                     Funestum diro transsodit vulnere telum,
                     Quo non cum reliquis, ad tractus temporis istos
                     Meue bonorum tot, communis laeticiaeue

                  Schipes.
                  
                     Graec. Culex estin aêre suspensa volitans, corporetam exili, vt oculi acumen nisi perspicacissimè cernentis facilè fallat: cutem autem quae feriat stimulo terebrat acerrimo: subtilitate & acumine tanto, vt quam volitantem conspicere nequeas pungentem ex ictu sentias: This Scnipes is a kynd of gnat flittering in the ayr, that stays vp it self by the wyngs: of substauns so fyne and small, as but by the ey of a sharp syght, it can not be discerned: any part of the body yet if it light vpō: with so sharp a styng dooth it pears, as which whoo sees not in flying, shall feel in sinartyng. This note is taken oout of Origens writings,Origen. Ho. mil. 4. in Exod. whoo was born at Adamantia in Grees, in which cuntree this kynd of gnat shoold seem too be: heer for the straungenes rehersed.—De Scnipe etiā Aristot. Hist. li. 8. ca. 3.

            Per Summum, Solum, Fortem, Potentem, Vnicum, Viuentem, Iustum, Misericordem, DEVM, praeter quem non est Deus: Cui soli in Maiestate trina, honor, gloria, laus, & gratiarum actio.
            FINIS.
